#!/usr/bin/env -S uv run --script
# /// script
# requires-python = ">=3.11"
# dependencies = [
#     "httpx>=0.27",
# ]
# ///
"""
capabilities — the capability manager.

This tool is designed to be invoked by agents. Run `capabilities help` to load
the full usage contract on demand.

The manager is the engine of the capability system: it installs capability
scripts into the machine registry, snapshots their self-descriptions, gates
them per project, composes the session context injection, and verifies the
whole arrangement. It is the SOLE WRITER of every shared file it manages —
the machine registry (~/.capabilities/<name>/), the project gate
(capabilities/settings.json), the project capabilities/.gitignore, the
generated skill, and the host hook wiring. Capability scripts never write
any of these.

ENVIRONMENT
  CAPABILITIES_HOME    machine registry root        (default ~/.capabilities)
  CAPABILITIES_SOURCE  catalogue base URL           (default the public repo, raw)
  CAPABILITIES_BIN     PATH dir for symlinks        (default ~/.local/bin or ~/bin,
                                                     whichever exists and is on PATH)
  CAPABILITIES_CONTEXT_PROMPT
                       optional project .env(.local) or process-env override
                       for the generated agent instruction paragraph.

MACHINE VERBS
  install <name> [--from <path|url> | --source ID] [--yes]
        Fetch the capability into the registry, symlink its executable onto
        PATH, snapshot `stub` + `manifest --json` (keyed by payload hash),
        scaffold credentials per the declared scope, surface declared
        post-install steps (--yes runs them), regenerate the skill.
        --from accepts: a script file, a bundle directory holding <name> or
        bin/<name>, a repo directory holding capabilities/<name>/bin/<name>, or
        a URL. Source directories, and script paths inside source directories,
        install the complete bundle, excluding bytecode/cache files. Default
        catalogue sources install from the public repo bundle when available.
        --source installs from one explicitly named registered source and records
        its repository/ref/commit provenance. An unqualified name remains an
        explicit request for the built-in official catalogue; custom sources
        never shadow it.
  uninstall <name> [--purge-credentials]
        Remove the PATH symlink and the registry entry; regenerate the skill.
        Credentials are kept and reported; --purge-credentials deletes the
        user-scope credential file after showing it.
  update [<name>]
        Re-fetch one capability (or all) from its recorded source; refresh
        snapshots; regenerate the skill.
  self-update
        Refresh the manager itself from the canonical source and re-point its
        PATH symlink (install.sh is the first-install bootstrap; this is the
        ongoing update). No-op when already current. The manager is not a
        capability, so it has no registry entry or snapshots.
  list
        Installed capabilities with summaries; inside a project, each entry
        also carries its gate state (enabled / disabled / ungated).
  search [QUERY] [--source ID]
        Search cached catalogues from the official and registered sources.
        Listing never executes catalogue capability code.
  source init ID [--remote GIT_URL]
        Create the canonical editable source workspace at
        ~/capabilities-sources/ID, initialize git, vendor the authoring contract,
        register it, and emit the exact authoring/publishing path.
  source add ID GIT_URL [--ref REF]
        Register and fetch a remote capability source into the manager-owned
        read-only cache. Existing git/SSH credentials are used; no token is stored.
  source clone ID GIT_URL [--ref REF]
        Clone an existing source into the canonical editable workspace and
        register it for authoring on this machine.
  source list | path ID | refresh [ID] | sync ID | check ID | index ID | remove ID
        Inspect sources, resolve the one editable path, refresh remote caches,
        verify every capability and generated catalogue, rebuild that catalogue
        after clean audits, or unregister a source. Removing never deletes an
        editable workspace.

PROJECT VERBS (run inside a consuming project)
  enable <name> / disable <name> [--deny]
        Write the project gate (capabilities/settings.json). enable also
        removes any harness deny rule for the capability; disable --deny
        additionally writes permissions.deny Bash(<name>:*) into
        .claude/settings.json — true enforcement where the host supports it.
  init [--claude] [--codex]
        Wire the project: scaffold capabilities/settings.json and the
        manager-owned capabilities/.gitignore; per host, wire the
        SessionStart hook/context compiler and generate the skill. No flags
        defaults to Claude Code wiring; Codex projects must pass --codex.
        The Codex compiler is manager-owned and overwritten on each init.
        Idempotent. When `.contextkit/config.toml` is present, init keeps the
        envelope and skill setup but skips host wiring: ContextKit owns it.
        A legacy project `.capabilities/` envelope is preflighted and migrated
        into visible `capabilities/`; content conflicts refuse before writes.
  context --claude|--codex|--fragment
        Compose the session injection from the gate + snapshots + project
        envelopes. --fragment prints the manager-owned Markdown block without
        writing host files; context owners such as ContextKit insert this output
        verbatim. The host modes place the same block where the host reads it (--claude:
        .claude/rules/CAPABILITIES.md; --codex: the capabilities fragment used
        by the generated .codex context compiler).
        Composition reads files only and degradation is per-capability, never
        whole; when Codex wiring exists, --codex also asks the generated local
        compiler to refresh .codex/generated/context.md. The generated agent
        instruction paragraph defaults to identifier persistence guidance and
        can be overridden with CAPABILITIES_CONTEXT_PROMPT in the project's
        .env/.env.local.
        Do not create or edit generated context files by hand; rerun this
        command (or the generated Codex compiler hook) after manual envelope
        changes. In a ContextKit-managed project (`.contextkit/config.toml`),
        ContextKit owns both host bindings and the combined context; the host
        modes delegate without writing and point to `contextkit build`, while
        --fragment remains the read-only provider surface ContextKit calls.
  ids <name>
        Render <name>'s project identifiers as markdown — the full labelled
        list the session context points to. (`<name> ids get|set|rm` is the
        per-value data interface on the capability itself.)

VERIFICATION VERBS
  doctor
        Reconcile machine registry ↔ snapshots ↔ project gate ↔ gitignore
        guard ↔ deny rules; report drift. Exit 0 clean, 7 drift found.
  audit <name> [--from <path>]
        Contract conformance: call the contract verbs, validate output
        shapes, exercise the gate (enabled / disabled / absent) in a
        sandbox, and byte-check the vendored preamble against
        contract/preamble.py. Exit 0 pass, 7 failures (incl. drift) found.
  sync-contract [--check]
        Stamp the canonical shared helpers from contract/preamble.py into the
        fenced regions (`capability core`, `connections`) of every
        capabilities/*/bin/*. The manager never participates. Idempotent.
        --check reports drift and exits 7 without writing.
  selfcheck
        Prove the repo's own wholeness (the inward companion to audit): the
        enforcer parses, every capability audits clean, both audit branches
        (core-only / connection-bearing) have a living green example and fire on
        a deliberate break, every standing rule names an enforcement the manager
        actually has, and every doc link resolves. Exit 0 whole, 7 otherwise.

AUTHORING VERBS (emit agent-executable instructions; judgment stays with the agent)
  new [<name> --source ID [--core-only]]
                   With no name, emit the authoring procedure. With a name,
                   create a canonical capability skeleton in that source;
                   generated contract regions are stamped by the manager.
  guide <authoring|repositories|publishing|contract>
                   Manager-bundled offline guidance for custom sources.
  conform <ref>    The procedure for bringing an existing script to the contract.
  groom <name>     The procedure for reviewing an installed capability.
  sanitize <name>  The procedure for reviewing this project's envelope for <name>.

I/O CONTRACT
  Success: JSON on stdout, except the documented Markdown renderers
  (`context --fragment`, `ids`). Failure: {"error": {"code", "message",
  "hint"?}} on stderr. Exit codes: 0 success, 2 auth, 3 not found,
  5 network, 6 input/validation, 7 drift or conformance failures
  (doctor/audit).
"""

from __future__ import annotations

